<misra_rule>
The target MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.14 is: The Standard Library function memcmp shall not be used to compare null terminated strings.

</misra_rule>
<instruction>

- explanation: The explanation of why other code fragments should NOT be investigated.

<target_code>
Here is the code of OS_SymbolLookup_Static:
```c
int32 OS_SymbolLookup_Static(cpuaddr *SymbolAddress, const char *SymbolName, const char *ModuleName)
{
    int32                      return_code = OS_ERR_NOT_IMPLEMENTED;
    OS_static_symbol_record_t *StaticSym   = OS_STATIC_SYMTABLE_SOURCE;

    while (StaticSym != NULL)
    {
        if (StaticSym->Name == NULL)
        {
            /* end of list --
             * Return "OS_ERROR" to indicate that an actual search was done
             * with a not-found result, vs. not searching at all. */
            return_code = OS_ERROR;
            break;
        }
        if (strcmp(StaticSym->Name, SymbolName) == 0 &&
            (ModuleName == NULL || strcmp(StaticSym->Module, ModuleName) == 0))
        {
            /* found matching symbol */
            *SymbolAddress = (cpuaddr)StaticSym->Address;
            return_code    = OS_SUCCESS;
            break;
        }

        ++StaticSym;
    }

    return return_code;
}
```
</target_code>
Please find suspicious code fragments in the code and report them. Other agents can not investigate other fragments that you do not report, so it is very important to find all suspicious fragments without missing any. Report the suspicious fragments AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.
explanation: I inspected the function for any use of the Standard Library function memcmp (including direct calls). No memcmp calls were found. The code uses strcmp to compare null-terminated strings (StaticSym->Name and StaticSym->Module vs. SymbolName/ModuleName), which is the intended string comparison function and not the memcmp forbidden by MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.14. The pointer NULL checks (StaticSym->Name == NULL and ModuleName == NULL) are explicit and not memcmp-based. Therefore there are no code fragments that violate or require investigation under Rule 21.14.
